Jeff Wicks, News24SA police. (Duncan Alfreds, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg - Attacks on police officers in Atteridgeville and Tembisa at the weekend have prompted a manhunt, Gauteng police said on Sunday.Police spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Lungelo Dlamini said that a policeman was killed on Friday in Atteridgeville.&ldquo;A 46-year-old warrant officer was attacked by three unknown men who were wearing balaclavas and demanded his vehicle while he was parked outside a house.&ldquo;In the ensuing struggle to take the car, the police officer was shot and killed and the suspects took his vehicle, a new VW Golf 6, and drove away. He was shot in the upper body and died at the scene,&rdquo; Dlamini said.&nbsp; &nbsp;In another incident, two police officers were attacked in the early hours of Saturday by two armed men in Tembisa.&ldquo;While the officers were waiting to pick one of their colleagues, they confronted two suspicious men whom they suspected to be in possession of a stolen a vehicle.&ldquo;There was a shoot-out between the suspects and the police.&nbsp; A policewoman was shot several times and wounded. The suspects managed to escape and they are still at large. [She] was taken to the hospital in a serious but stable condition. Her colleague was not injured,&rdquo; Dlamini added. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.